		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1ac8bf1e06012df4d9fb971dd984ac6a?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fthepioneerwoman.com%2Fcooking%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Fmulti%2Fimages%2Fcomment-avatar-3.gif%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />		<div class="comment-text">
			<h4>Dana <span>On Tuesday, October 26 at 5:20 am</span></h4>
			<p>Does the ratio of brine to turkey size matter? I brined two years ago and the turkey came out too salty for my taste. It was moist though. Just wondering if I should cut back on the salt for a smaller bird? Thanks!</p>
					</div>
		<div class="clr"></div>
	<div class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-2056205">
		<span class="comment-bubble"></span>
		<p class="comment-number"></p>
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0a4a24408ae6dc3aed050ddda44a2552?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fthepioneerwoman.com%2Fcooking%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Fmulti%2Fimages%2Fcomment-avatar-3.gif%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />		<div class="comment-text">
			<h4>Amy <span>On Tuesday, October 26 at 7:09 am</span></h4>
			<p>It is much smaller, than yes.  Ree&#8217;s ratio would be good for anything 18+, but I would cut down to 1 cup of Kosher salt for anything less.  If it is under 12, than maybe go to 3/4 cup.</p>
