	<div class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-2056297">
		<span class="comment-bubble"></span>
		<p class="comment-number"></p>
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/2794dfce3f3230c4af1cfde712110f09?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fthepioneerwoman.com%2Fcooking%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Fmulti%2Fimages%2Fcomment-avatar-3.gif%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />		<div class="comment-text">
			<h4>Natasha <span>On Tuesday, October 26 at 11:14 am</span></h4>
			<p>Like Ree said, just halve the recipe for a smaller bird. </p>
<p>Just make sure you rinse the bird really well.  I&#8217;ve been brining my turkeys for several years, and the key to making sure you don&#8217;t end up with a salty bird is to rinse it completely, inside and out.  I also like to pat it dry completely or even let it air dry in the fridge overnight to ensure the skin gets crispy and brown and doesn&#8217;t steam in the oven.</p>
					</div>
		<div class="clr"></div>
