	<div class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-2141372">
		<span class="comment-bubble"></span>
		<p class="comment-number"></p>
		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/f9c272e6de815768e8a3ae6eab4d1eb7?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fthepioneerwoman.com%2Fcooking%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Fmulti%2Fimages%2Fcomment-avatar-3.gif%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />		<div class="comment-text">
			<h4>JimL <span>On Wednesday, November 24 at 7:37 pm</span></h4>
			<p>from a chemistry standpoint, it really doesn&#8217;t matter the size of the bird.  The salinity level of the liquid is just that, and changing the salinity of the solution is not going to change the amount of salt that gets retained in the meat.  Equalibrium is equalibrium.</p>
<p>The beauty of brining is that the liquid is miscible with the liquids in the meat, so it carries the flavors in.</p>
<p>Never trust a chemist that doesn&#8217;t cook.</p>
					</div>
		<div class="clr"></div>
