	<div class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="comment-2140475">
		<span class="comment-bubble"></span>
		<p class="comment-number"></p>
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/28634c3913490af006531bab37f2980d?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fthepioneerwoman.com%2Fcooking%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Fmulti%2Fimages%2Fcomment-avatar-3.gif%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />		<div class="comment-text">
			<h4>SuperMomJC <span>On Sunday, November 21 at 4:25 pm</span></h4>
			<p>I&#8217;ve been a chef for many years.  A traditional brine is equal parts kosher salt and sugar, (sugar of your choice, although I usually use dark brown sugar as the molassas in it adds flavor).  You need both the salt and sugar to cause the molecular osmosis that makes the meat moister&#8230;. Then you can add any additional flavorings you like.  My personal favorite is crystallized ginger and whole allspice with a mix of fresh herbs.  If you did not see favorable results from brining &#8211; you did something wrong.  Probably no sugar or not enough salt, perhaps you over cooked it slightly or didn&#8217;t let the bird rest (20 minutes before carving an absolute necessity).  If your bird is salty then you probably didn&#8217;t use kosher salt or didn&#8217;t use equal parts of sugar.  The drippings will be salty but the meat shouldn&#8217;t be&#8230;  </p>
<p>You can brine any meat or poultry&#8230;. In my opinion pork is the other meat that benefits greatly from a little brine.  Usually only takes from 20 to 60 minutes for 4 to 6 pork chops and the difference is remarkable.  </p>
<p>I am definately going to try your recipe with apple cider and oranges this year for my turkey and maybe a nice pork loin roast. Yum!</p>
					</div>
		<div class="clr"></div>
</div>
