		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/64534fc0b3f001af6dc0d8735039e7b7?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fthepioneerwoman.com%2Fcooking%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Fmulti%2Fimages%2Fcomment-avatar-3.gif%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />		<div class="comment-text">
			<h4>Jen Hudok <span>On Tuesday, October 26 at 9:00 am</span></h4>
			<p>Love the brined birds! I also started doing it when I saw it on Good Eats. If you are interested in the reason brining makes the bird juicy, there is a great little clip on the Thanksgiving episode that explains it very well. Also a la AB, I use a big sports water cooler. Obviously, it is dedicated to the once-a-year bird. Makes it very easy to drain off the brine and keeps it cool without taking up room in the fridge. I use frozen birds, but I pay close attention to the ingredients and processing info on the package.</p>
<p>Ree, I am going to try your brine this year! I&#8217;ve been looking to change it up and play with the ingredients a little.</p>
