	<div class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="comment-2056252">
		<span class="comment-bubble"></span>
		<p class="comment-number">65</p>
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/06f1a7e18f6d9ae447ecc2a6c1a35ccb?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fthepioneerwoman.com%2Fcooking%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Fmulti%2Fimages%2Fcomment-avatar-3.gif%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />		<div class="comment-text">
			<h4>Kathy <span>On Tuesday, October 26 at 9:01 am</span></h4>
			<p>I&#8217;ve been brining the turkey for the past several years.  Have always used a frozen turkey and have not had any problems with it being overly salty.  It is just delicious.  Between brining and using a cooking bag for the roasting I never have to worry about a dried out turkey again.  I put an XL or XXL ziplock bag into a large tall, narrow stockpot I have, then put the turkey in there, then fill with the brine.  That way the whole thing is always covered in brine and I don&#8217;t have to worry about flipping it. (It&#8217;s just not polite to flip the bird <img src='http://static.thepioneerwoman.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif' alt=';-)' class='wp-smiley' />   )</p>
					</div>
