	<div class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-2056273">
		<span class="comment-bubble"></span>
		<p class="comment-number">78</p>
		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/d6ed2c8178928fc053b6bbb65cf6bce2?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fthepioneerwoman.com%2Fcooking%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Fmulti%2Fimages%2Fcomment-avatar-3.gif%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />		<div class="comment-text">
			<h4>Julie <span>On Tuesday, October 26 at 10:03 am</span></h4>
			<p>I brine all my poultry and this is one of my favorite brines for Turkey.  I usually add thyme, fennel seed, 4 cloves whole garlic, and about 2 tbsp liquid smoke to the mix.  The only thing with brining turkey is you get far less drippings than you would with an unbrined bird, so don&#8217;t count on drippings for gravey.  Also, it takes about 45 less time to cook a brined bird, so plan ahead.  One last word of advice, if you are going to deep fry a brined bird, don&#8217;t use a brine with sugar &#8211; it will cause the skin to appear burned.</p>
					</div>
		<div class="clr"></div>
</div>
